            <title><![CDATA[Blog Post Ideas]]></title>
            <link>https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas</link>
            <guid>https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas</guid>
            <pubDate>Sun, 14 Jun 2026 06:37:44 GMT</pubDate>
            <description><![CDATA[{/ truncate /}]]></description>
            <content:encoded><![CDATA[
<h2 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="incident-postmortems">Incident Postmortems<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#incident-postmortems" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Incident Postmortems" title="Direct link to Incident Postmortems" translate="no">​</a></h2>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="gke-node-pool-failure-how-we-lost-3-hours-to-a-misconfigured-autoscaler">GKE Node Pool Failure: How We Lost 3 Hours to a Misconfigured Autoscaler<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#gke-node-pool-failure-how-we-lost-3-hours-to-a-misconfigured-autoscaler" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to GKE Node Pool Failure: How We Lost 3 Hours to a Misconfigured Autoscaler" title="Direct link to GKE Node Pool Failure: How We Lost 3 Hours to a Misconfigured Autoscaler" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>A node pool rollout triggered a cascade of pod evictions during peak traffic. Walk through the timeline, the initial misdiagnosis (it looked like an application bug), and the config change that fixed it.</p>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="cloud-run-cold-start-outage-when-concurrency-limits-arent-what-you-think">Cloud Run Cold Start Outage: When Concurrency Limits Aren't What You Think<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#cloud-run-cold-start-outage-when-concurrency-limits-arent-what-you-think" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Cloud Run Cold Start Outage: When Concurrency Limits Aren't What You Think" title="Direct link to Cloud Run Cold Start Outage: When Concurrency Limits Aren't What You Think" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>A deployment during high-traffic hours exposed cold start latencies 10x worse than expected. The root cause: misunderstanding how Cloud Run allocates container instances under concurrent load. Details on the fix and revised concurrency settings.</p>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="terraform-state-corruption-lessons-from-a-production-state-lock-failure">Terraform State Corruption: Lessons from a Production State Lock Failure<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#terraform-state-corruption-lessons-from-a-production-state-lock-failure" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Terraform State Corruption: Lessons from a Production State Lock Failure" title="Direct link to Terraform State Corruption: Lessons from a Production State Lock Failure" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>An automated pipeline left state locked after a network interruption mid-apply. What we tried first, what made it worse, and the manual state surgery that finally recovered the infrastructure without a full recreation.</p>
<hr>
<h2 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="cloud-run-deep-dives">Cloud Run Deep Dives<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#cloud-run-deep-dives" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Cloud Run Deep Dives" title="Direct link to Cloud Run Deep Dives" translate="no">​</a></h2>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="deploying-cloud-run-services-with-terraform-a-production-grade-module">Deploying Cloud Run Services with Terraform: A Production-Grade Module<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#deploying-cloud-run-services-with-terraform-a-production-grade-module" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Deploying Cloud Run Services with Terraform: A Production-Grade Module" title="Direct link to Deploying Cloud Run Services with Terraform: A Production-Grade Module" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>Why the official Google provider examples fall short for real teams. A module that handles service accounts, VPC connector routing, and revision tagging with zero-downtime deploys.</p>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="cloud-run-concurrency-what-the-docs-dont-tell-you">Cloud Run Concurrency: What the Docs Don't Tell You<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#cloud-run-concurrency-what-the-docs-dont-tell-you" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Cloud Run Concurrency: What the Docs Don't Tell You" title="Direct link to Cloud Run Concurrency: What the Docs Don't Tell You" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>The difference between <code>--concurrency</code> and the container instance limit. How to calculate realistic concurrency values from request patterns and avoid the "all instances busy" errors under burst traffic.</p>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="connecting-cloud-run-to-cloud-sql-without-exposing-credentials">Connecting Cloud Run to Cloud SQL Without Exposing Credentials<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#connecting-cloud-run-to-cloud-sql-without-exposing-credentials" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Connecting Cloud Run to Cloud SQL Without Exposing Credentials" title="Direct link to Connecting Cloud Run to Cloud SQL Without Exposing Credentials" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>Private Service Connect, VPC access connectors, and the Secret Manager pattern that keeps database credentials out of environment variables entirely.</p>
<hr>
<h2 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="pubsub">Pub/Sub<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#pubsub" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Pub/Sub" title="Direct link to Pub/Sub" translate="no">​</a></h2>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="pubsub-ordering-keys-when-to-use-them-and-when-not-to">Pub/Sub Ordering Keys: When to Use Them and When Not To<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#pubsub-ordering-keys-when-to-use-them-and-when-not-to" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Pub/Sub Ordering Keys: When to Use Them and When Not To" title="Direct link to Pub/Sub Ordering Keys: When to Use Them and When Not To" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>Ordering keys guarantee processing order within a region but add latency and cost. Real-world guidance on when ordering matters (spoiler: less often than you think) and how to structure messages for parallel processing when it doesn't.</p>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="setting-up-dead-letter-queues-without-losing-messages-in-transit">Setting Up Dead Letter Queues Without Losing Messages in Transit<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#setting-up-dead-letter-queues-without-losing-messages-in-transit" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Setting Up Dead Letter Queues Without Losing Messages in Transit" title="Direct link to Setting Up Dead Letter Queues Without Losing Messages in Transit" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>A misconfigured DLQ setup can silently drop messages during deployment. Walk through the subscription retry policy, dead letter topic configuration, and the Cloud Function that republishes corrected messages.</p>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="exactly-once-delivery-in-pubsub-what-it-actually-means">Exactly-Once Delivery in Pub/Sub: What It Actually Means<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#exactly-once-delivery-in-pubsub-what-it-actually-means" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Exactly-Once Delivery in Pub/Sub: What It Actually Means" title="Direct link to Exactly-Once Delivery in Pub/Sub: What It Actually Means" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>Exactly-once suppresses duplicates at the subscriber level, but it doesn't prevent application-level double processing. The idempotency patterns required to make it work end-to-end.</p>
<hr>
<h2 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="kubernetes-debugging">Kubernetes Debugging<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#kubernetes-debugging" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Kubernetes Debugging" title="Direct link to Kubernetes Debugging" translate="no">​</a></h2>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="debugging-crashloopbackoff-a-systematic-checklist">Debugging CrashLoopBackOff: A Systematic Checklist<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#debugging-crashloopbackoff-a-systematic-checklist" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Debugging CrashLoopBackOff: A Systematic Checklist" title="Direct link to Debugging CrashLoopBackOff: A Systematic Checklist" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>The diagnosis path from <code>kubectl describe</code> to container logs to security policy enforcement. What to check at each layer and the common root causes that get overlooked (liveness probes timing out before the app is ready is the #1 offender).</p>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="oomkilled-in-gke-finding-the-real-memory-limit">OOMKilled in GKE: Finding the Real Memory Limit<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#oomkilled-in-gke-finding-the-real-memory-limit" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to OOMKilled in GKE: Finding the Real Memory Limit" title="Direct link to OOMKilled in GKE: Finding the Real Memory Limit" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>kubectl top and Prometheus metrics don't always match what Kubernetes thinks is the limit. The kernel oom killer, cgroup memory soft limits, and how to tune GKE node memory allocation to avoid premature evictions.</p>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="dns-resolution-failures-in-kubernetes-coredns-kube-dns-and-the-resolvconf-trap">DNS Resolution Failures in Kubernetes: CoreDNS, kube-dns, and the resolv.conf Trap<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#dns-resolution-failures-in-kubernetes-coredns-kube-dns-and-the-resolvconf-trap" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to DNS Resolution Failures in Kubernetes: CoreDNS, kube-dns, and the resolv.conf Trap" title="Direct link to DNS Resolution Failures in Kubernetes: CoreDNS, kube-dns, and the resolv.conf Trap" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>Pod DNS resolution slowing to a crawl after scaling events. The interaction between kubelet's resolv.conf generation and CoreDNS's forwarding cache, and why increasing replica count isn't the fix.</p>
<hr>
<h2 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="cicd">CI/CD<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#cicd" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to CI/CD" title="Direct link to CI/CD" translate="no">​</a></h2>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="github-actions--gcp-workload-identity-secure-ci-without-static-keys">GitHub Actions + GCP Workload Identity: Secure CI Without Static Keys<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#github-actions--gcp-workload-identity-secure-ci-without-static-keys" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to GitHub Actions + GCP Workload Identity: Secure CI Without Static Keys" title="Direct link to GitHub Actions + GCP Workload Identity: Secure CI Without Static Keys" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>Why long-lived service account keys are a compliance risk. A step-by-step implementation of Workload Identity Federation for GitHub Actions, including the IAM bindings and the token caching that keeps builds fast.</p>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="running-terraform-plan-and-apply-in-github-actions-without-destroying-production">Running Terraform Plan and Apply in GitHub Actions Without Destroying Production<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#running-terraform-plan-and-apply-in-github-actions-without-destroying-production" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Running Terraform Plan and Apply in GitHub Actions Without Destroying Production" title="Direct link to Running Terraform Plan and Apply in GitHub Actions Without Destroying Production" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>The pull request workflow that makes Terraform changes safe: plan generation in CI, formatted output comments on PRs, required reviewers for apply stages, and the environment restriction that prevents direct main-branch applies.</p>
<hr>
<h2 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="cost-optimization">Cost Optimization<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#cost-optimization" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Cost Optimization" title="Direct link to Cost Optimization" translate="no">​</a></h2>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="rightsizing-gke-nodes-moving-from-over-provisioned-to-efficient">Rightsizing GKE Nodes: Moving from Over-Provisioned to Efficient<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#rightsizing-gke-nodes-moving-from-over-provisioned-to-efficient" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Rightsizing GKE Nodes: Moving from Over-Provisioned to Efficient" title="Direct link to Rightsizing GKE Nodes: Moving from Over-Provisioned to Efficient" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>A node pool was running at 40% CPU average but pods were still being evicted. The analysis that revealed memory was the real constraint, and the migration from n1-standard to e2-custom machine types that cut costs 35%.</p>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="cloud-storage-lifecycle-policies-avoiding-the-lifecycle-rule-pitfalls">Cloud Storage Lifecycle Policies: Avoiding the Lifecycle Rule Pitfalls<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#cloud-storage-lifecycle-policies-avoiding-the-lifecycle-rule-pitfalls" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Cloud Storage Lifecycle Policies: Avoiding the Lifecycle Rule Pitfalls" title="Direct link to Cloud Storage Lifecycle Policies: Avoiding the Lifecycle Rule Pitfalls" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>Lifecycle transitions failing silently because of versioning conflicts or custom time conditions. The bucket configuration that actually works for log archival, and the Storage Insights Report that surfaces what you didn't know you were paying for.</p>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="bigquery-slot-management-on-demand-vs-flat-rate-decision-framework">BigQuery Slot Management: On-Demand vs. Flat-Rate Decision Framework<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#bigquery-slot-management-on-demand-vs-flat-rate-decision-framework" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to BigQuery Slot Management: On-Demand vs. Flat-Rate Decision Framework" title="Direct link to BigQuery Slot Management: On-Demand vs. Flat-Rate Decision Framework" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>When flat-rate commitment is worth it and when on-demand pricing wins. A spreadsheet model for calculating break-even based on query volume, and how to run a controlled experiment before committing.</p>
<hr>
<h2 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="gcp-interview-preparation">GCP Interview Preparation<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#gcp-interview-preparation" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to GCP Interview Preparation" title="Direct link to GCP Interview Preparation" translate="no">​</a></h2>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="gcp-architecture-case-study-designing-a-multi-region-api-with-999-sla">GCP Architecture Case Study: Designing a Multi-Region API with 99.9% SLA<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#gcp-architecture-case-study-designing-a-multi-region-api-with-999-sla" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to GCP Architecture Case Study: Designing a Multi-Region API with 99.9% SLA" title="Direct link to GCP Architecture Case Study: Designing a Multi-Region API with 99.9% SLA" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>Walk through a real interview-style design: regional vs. multi-region buckets, Cloud Run placement, load balancer geographic routing, and the tradeoffs between consistency and availability at global scale.</p>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="iam-scenario-questions-when-to-use-roles-workload-identity-or-service-accounts">IAM Scenario Questions: When to Use Roles, Workload Identity, or Service Accounts<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#iam-scenario-questions-when-to-use-roles-workload-identity-or-service-accounts" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to IAM Scenario Questions: When to Use Roles, Workload Identity, or Service Accounts" title="Direct link to IAM Scenario Questions: When to Use Roles, Workload Identity, or Service Accounts" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>Common IAM interview traps: when a predefined role has too many permissions, why service account keys are a red flag, and how to design least-privilege access for a CI/CD pipeline accessing multiple projects.</p>
<h3 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="gcp-pricing-deep-dive-calculating-total-cost-for-a-production-workload">GCP Pricing Deep Dive: Calculating Total Cost for a Production Workload<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/post-ideas#gcp-pricing-deep-dive-calculating-total-cost-for-a-production-workload" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to GCP Pricing Deep Dive: Calculating Total Cost for a Production Workload" title="Direct link to GCP Pricing Deep Dive: Calculating Total Cost for a Production Workload" translate="no">​</a></h3>
<p>The interview questions that trip up candidates who only know on-demand pricing: committed use discounts, sustained use discounts, preemptible VM savings, and the hidden costs in egress and inter-region traffic.</p>]]></content:encoded>
        </item>
        <item>
            <title><![CDATA[Terraform Module Patterns for Production]]></title>
            <link>https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/terraform-module-patterns</link>
            <guid>https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/terraform-module-patterns</guid>
            <pubDate>Thu, 05 Jun 2025 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate>
            <description><![CDATA[Reusable module design patterns used in real-world infrastructure with Terraform and Google Cloud.]]></description>
            <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>After managing infrastructure across multiple projects, I’ve distilled some <strong>Terraform module patterns</strong> that keep code clean, reusable, and maintainable.</p>
<!-- -->
<hr>
<h2 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="the-layout-pattern">The Layout Pattern<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/terraform-module-patterns#the-layout-pattern" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to The Layout Pattern" title="Direct link to The Layout Pattern" translate="no">​</a></h2>
<div class="language-text codeBlockContainer_Ckt0 theme-code-block" style="--prism-color:#393A34;--prism-background-color:#f6f8fa"><div class="codeBlockContent_QJqH"><pre tabindex="0" class="prism-code language-text codeBlock_bY9V thin-scrollbar" style="color:#393A34;background-color:#f6f8fa"><code class="codeBlockLines_e6Vv"><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">modules/</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">  gce_instance/</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">    main.tf</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">    variables.tf</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">    outputs.tf</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">  vpc/</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">    main.tf</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">    variables.tf</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">    outputs.tf</span><br></div></code></pre></div></div>
<p>Each module:</p>
<ul>
<li class="">Has a <strong>single responsibility</strong></li>
<li class="">Exposes only <strong>intentional inputs</strong> via <code>variables.tf</code></li>
<li class="">Returns <strong>predictable outputs</strong> via <code>outputs.tf</code></li>
</ul>
<h2 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="version-pinning">Version Pinning<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/terraform-module-patterns#version-pinning" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Version Pinning" title="Direct link to Version Pinning" translate="no">​</a></h2>
<p>Always pin provider and module versions in production.</p>
<div class="language-hcl codeBlockContainer_Ckt0 theme-code-block" style="--prism-color:#393A34;--prism-background-color:#f6f8fa"><div class="codeBlockContent_QJqH"><pre tabindex="0" class="prism-code language-hcl codeBlock_bY9V thin-scrollbar" style="color:#393A34;background-color:#f6f8fa"><code class="codeBlockLines_e6Vv"><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">terraform {</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">  required_providers {</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">    google = {</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">      source  = "hashicorp/google"</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">      version = "~&gt; 5.0"</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">    }</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">  }</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">}</span><br></div></code></pre></div></div>
<h2 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="using-for_each-over-count">Using <code>for_each</code> Over <code>count</code><a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/terraform-module-patterns#using-for_each-over-count" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to using-for_each-over-count" title="Direct link to using-for_each-over-count" translate="no">​</a></h2>
<p>Use <code>for_each</code> for named resources to avoid reordering issues.</p>
<div class="language-hcl codeBlockContainer_Ckt0 theme-code-block" style="--prism-color:#393A34;--prism-background-color:#f6f8fa"><div class="codeBlockContent_QJqH"><pre tabindex="0" class="prism-code language-hcl codeBlock_bY9V thin-scrollbar" style="color:#393A34;background-color:#f6f8fa"><code class="codeBlockLines_e6Vv"><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">variable "subnets" {</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">  type = map(object({</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">    cidr = string</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">    region = string</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">  }))</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">}</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain" style="display:inline-block"></span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">resource "google_compute_subnetwork" "default" {</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">  for_each = var.subnets</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain" style="display:inline-block"></span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">  name          = each.key</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">  ip_cidr_range = each.value.cidr</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">  region        = each.value.region</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">  network       = google_compute_network.vpc.id</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">}</span><br></div></code></pre></div></div>
<h2 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="remote-state-with-gcs">Remote State with GCS<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/terraform-module-patterns#remote-state-with-gcs" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Remote State with GCS" title="Direct link to Remote State with GCS" translate="no">​</a></h2>
<p>Store state remotely to enable team collaboration.</p>
<div class="language-hcl codeBlockContainer_Ckt0 theme-code-block" style="--prism-color:#393A34;--prism-background-color:#f6f8fa"><div class="codeBlockContent_QJqH"><pre tabindex="0" class="prism-code language-hcl codeBlock_bY9V thin-scrollbar" style="color:#393A34;background-color:#f6f8fa"><code class="codeBlockLines_e6Vv"><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">terraform {</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">  backend "gcs" {</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">    bucket = "my-tf-state-bucket"</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">    prefix = "prod/infrastructure"</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">  }</span><br></div><div class="token-line" style="color:#393A34"><span class="token plain">}</span><br></div></code></pre></div></div>
<h2 class="anchor anchorTargetStickyNavbar_Vzrq" id="summary">Summary<a href="https://souravgke052-coder.github.io/devops-blog/blog/terraform-module-patterns#summary" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Summary" title="Direct link to Summary" translate="no">​</a></h2>
<ul>
<li class="">Use modules for reusable components</li>
<li class="">Pin provider versions</li>
<li class="">Prefer maps and <code>for_each</code> over lists and <code>count</code></li>
<li class="">Always use remote state in production</li>
</ul>
<p>What patterns do you use? Let me know in the comments!</p>]]></content:encoded>
